CAPE TOWN - Alleged Parliament arsonist, Zandile Mafe, may have to undergo a 30--day psychiatric evaluation after a district surgeon diagnosed him with paranoid schizophrenia.This emerged during Mafe's second court appearance at the Cape Town Magistrate's Court on Tuesday morning.According to State prosecutor Helene Booysen, Mafe, who faces six charges, had been taken for consultation with district surgeon Zelda van Tonder where he had been diagnosed.The State has now made an application for Mafe to undergo a 30-day observation period at Valkenberg Psychiatric Hospital to determine whether he is fit to stand trial.Mafe, who was clean shaven and dressed in a black blazer and collared blue shirt during Tuesday's proceedings, is accused of having gained access to Parliament where he allegedly stole items – according to the charge sheet "laptop, crockery and documents" – and further accused of having started the fire which razed Parliament's Old and New Assembly buildings.A new charge was added to Mafe's charge sheet, which relates to the Contravention of the Terrorist Act, while the State abandoned the count which related to the damage of essential Infrastructure.This while Mafe's bail application is still being pursued.At his last court appearance, the matter was postponed for further investigation and bail information while Mafe remained in custody.Meanwhile, Advocate Dali Mpofu has officially come on record as senior counsel for Mafe.The matter continues. Cape Times